posts.content:
I am grateful to be featured in this thoughtful post about redefining success. 

Like, my journey has shifted from external metrics to finding fulfillment in balance, sustainability, and impact.

Breaking free from the constant hustle helped me realize that success isn't about grinding ‚Äì it's about creating space for what truly matters.

True success for me now means these non-negotiables:
-Working out each morning and not taking client calls until 10am.
-Reserving time for writing and creating each week.
-Investing in my own growth with a Coach.
-A morning routine that's both calm, creative, and energizing.

Is it time to define your non-negotiables?

What's your definition of success evolved to become?
posts.commentAdded: Love this approach to success! Its inspiring to see you prioritize fulfillment and balance. My non-negotiables are similar; lets keep redefining together!

posts.name:
Alex Turnbull
Alex Turnbull
posts.content:
The path most founders don't talk about:

1- Build a SaaS without validating product-market fit
2- Tweet about your stealth startup
3- Land 2-3 enterprise deals through network
4- Seed: $3M at $15M cap (20% dilution)
5- Series A: $10M at $50M cap (20% dilution)
6- Series B: $30M at $150M cap (25% dilution)
7- Final ownership: 7%
8- Monthly burn: $800K
9- Team size: 120 people
10- Board meetings promising "enterprise motion"
11- Run out of runway at month 22
12- "Strategic exit" for $100M
13- Founder payout: $7M after 7 years (before taxes)
14- Become a Twitter thought leader posting about your "successful exit"

 The bootstrap path nobody glamorizes:
1- Find a problem you're obsessed with
2- Talk to 100+ customers before writing code
3- Build the ONE thing they'll pay for
4- Get paying customers from beta launch
5- Stay at 100% ownership
6- Keep team under 25 people
7- Focus on unit economics
8- $10M ARR at 50% margins
9- Take home $3-5M/year
10- Exit available anytime for $30-40M
11- Or keep running it forever
12- Complete freedom to choose

Here‚Äôs the math that actually matters for founders:

VC Path ROI:

- 7 years of stress
- 3 rounds of dilution
- Loss of control
- $7M one-time payout
- If you're lucky (<1% chance)

Bootstrap Path ROI:

- Build with customer money
- Keep 100% ownership
- $5M annual profit
- $30-40M exit option always there
- Thousands have done it
- Complete freedom to:
- Work 1 hour or 100 hours
- Sell or scale
- Take profits or reinvest

Build for freedom, not exits.

comments.commentText:
Nice post. You don't necessarily need to embark on the risky mission of building a "very big company" to get a life changing outcome for yourself.

$40M exit on a $10M ARR business might only take 2000 customers a $5/k year or 1000 customers on $10k/year.

More achievable than scaling to the moon and leaves room for optionality vs having to IPO or be strategically acquired to get meaningful returns for investors. After dilution, more stress and more risk, you might get a similar or even smaller outcome on the venture track.

posts.commentAdded: Great insights! üöÄ Choosing the right path is crucial. Freedom and ownership can lead to sustainable success. Lets build for impact!

posts.content:
5 Things I Do in the First 60 Days of Starting a New Role That Help Me Stand Out and Boost My Success Rate

As someone who has thrived in Customer Success and Account Management roles, I‚Äôve developed a few key strategies that ensure I hit the ground running.

Some might call these steps "extra," but they‚Äôve consistently helped me stand out and make a meaningful impact.

 Take a look below and let me know in the comments: What would YOU add to this list?

1Ô∏è‚É£ Schedule 1:1s with Cross-Functional Partners and Teammates:

While onboarding, I use this time to reach out (usually via Slack, after gauging company culture) and introduce myself to team members across different departments. These conversations give me:

1. A clear lay of the land
2. Insights into who‚Äôs who and what‚Äôs happening behind the scenes
3. A chance to align myself with company priorities early on

This approach isn‚Äôt just networking; it‚Äôs strategic alignment. These relationships often pay dividends down the line.

 In my most recent role, I scheduled 17 one-on-ones over the course of two weeks! This intentional effort helped me feel extremely connected and supported by the two-month mark. Building these relationships early created a strong foundation for collaboration and trust.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Get Crystal Clear on Your OKRs and KPIs:

Understanding exactly how my success will be measured is a game-changer. I make it a priority to discuss key metrics with my manager and other stakeholders to ensure I‚Äôm focused on the right priorities from day one.

I also create a project or system to track my progress. This ensures I always have the latest and greatest insights on where I stand and can back it up with clear documentation. Having this visibility keeps me accountable and prepared for any performance discussions.

 Asana is my all-time favorite tool for this! I project manage nearly EVERY aspect of my life, personal and professional.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Build Your Organizational Toolkit:

The first 60 days are the perfect time to create systems that set you up for long-term success. Here‚Äôs what I focus on:

1. A note-taking system to capture key insights from onboarding sessions and calls.
2. A task management workflow to stay on top of daily and weekly priorities.
3. A calendar strategy that includes blocking focus time and scheduling recurring meetings with key collaborators like managers, account executives, or solutions engineers.
4. A praise bank system to store positive feedback, performance reviews, and personal success milestones. This also includes a space to track areas for improvement, ensuring I have a clear, balanced view of my growth and contributions.

Being organized early keeps me proactive, prepared, and ready to adapt to any challenges.

What would you add to this list? Has anything resonated with you or sparked new ideas?

Share your thoughts in the comments!

comments.commentText: I love your approach, especially scheduling 1:1s early to build those strong connections. I‚Äôd also add seeking feedback from peers and leaders during those first 60 days; it shows commitment to growth and helps refine your approach for long-term success!

Selling enterprise solutions? 
Stop onboarding your enterprise reps like SMB reps.


Had an insightful conversation with my great friend(Sales Enablement Manager at MATRIXX Software, ex-BlackBerry) who transformed a "here's your Dropbox link" onboarding into a competitive advantage.

At a time when his competitors were 30x larger and giving away competing products for free, he proved that excellence in onboarding could level the playing field.


Here are 4 pillars of high-touch onboarding that most companies miss:

- Know your reps as humans first - even something as basic as pronouncing their name correctly sets the tone for their entire journey
- Master their role better than they do - you're their guide through uncharted territory
- Map out their learning journey - it's not just what they need to know, but when they need to know it
- Build their network intentionally - connect them with the right people at the right time


In the full episode, we covered:

- How to build a high-touch program with zero budget
- The real cost of rushing reps into the field
- Why enterprise software demands different onboarding than transactional SaaS
- Why enterprise reps need more than relationship skills to win deals


Check out the full conversation in the comments

posts.commentAdded: Great insights! Onboarding is crucial in today‚Äôs competitive landscape. These pillars can truly set enterprise reps up for success. üëè #SalesExcellence
